I think the idea isn't to build a network from an XML file but to generate the XML file from the net.
Like you showed above, you deserialise in to the net, then you call dlib::net_to_xml.

I agree the kwallet implementation is a little funky; setting static attributes in the `connected` method is awkward, and maybe could be improved. What's worse is that the 'service' name is being embedded in the "key", whatever that's supposed to be.

Still, that issue is separate from the original critique, which was suggesting that the backend selection on import is somehow preventing the creation of a different backend. I don't think it is, but if you want to file a separate ticket on that mechanism, you may.

> You would need to implement a init on the backends that took the config and stop setting it in connected().

You could do that now with a bit of a hack:

```
class TweakedKWallet(kwallet.DBusKeyring):
    @property
    def folder(self):
        return vars(self).get('folder', 'Python')

    @folder.setter
    def folder(self, val):
        "ignore the value"

    @property
    def appid(self):
        return vars(self).get('appid', 'Python program')

    @appid.setter
    def appid(self, val):
        "ignore the value"

backend = TweakedKWallet()
vars(backend).update(folder='custom folder', appid='custom appid')
keyring.core.set_keyring(backend)
```

I acknowledge that is ugly and hacky, but I suspect it would enable what you seek.

Perhaps it does make sense to allow the folder and appid to be customized, but since the main API of keyring is meant to be the get/set/delete password functions, and those are meant to be invoked without additional parameters, I struggle a bit to see how a suitable values would be solicited.

> The Windows backend also needs to have configuration data to set the "TargetName" value following MSDN guidelines. Google for CredWrite to get the MSDN for the API then click thru to the CREDENTIAL struct for the docs on use of the values.

I'm familiar with the API. Have you read the code? The TargetName is set to the 'service' value.

> It may well be the case that fixes the API as I need is not possible

Perhaps you could start by describing the use case you have and how you expect keyring could be adapted to fit that use case?

@keleshev I give you example few posts ago. You can do things like class `Import`, so you can create your own set of extensions to Schema on top of Schema without editing any part of it. That's powerful, you can  control your `validate` methods using `**kwargs` parameters.

There is nothing really hard, check my example (especially doc tests) and see that output changes when you put different kwarg. I'm using exactly smth like this to serialize and unserialize django models for my planned in time  notifications arguments (to not store models) and in the same time having type validations for them! That's just great!
In my case I push real objects and they all are converted to id's when using `schema.validate(data)` and convert them back to objects few months later when using `validate(data, import=True)`.

