Hi @duduklein, so you are proposing we can organize the resource_mapping like this right?
```
'thread': {    
    'resource': 'threads',
    'subresources': {
        'close': {
            'resource': 'threads/close.json',
            'docs': 'https://disqus.com/api/docs/threads/close/',
            'methods': ['POST'],
        },
        'create': {
            'resource': 'threads/create.json',
            'docs': 'https://disqus.com/api/docs/threads/create/',
            'methods': ['POST'],
        },
        'details': {
            'resource': 'threads/details.json',
            'docs': 'https://disqus.com/api/docs/threads/details/',
            'methods': ['GET'],
        },
    }
}
```
At first glance the way tortilla does to this looks interesting and natural. But it comes with some problems:

1. In the example above, as much as there are many resources with a url of the type 'threads/{something}.json', it's possible an API where there isn't an endpoint 'threads/', so doing `api.threads.get()` will actually lead the user to try to fetch an invalid endpoint. This is a bit misleading.
2. Tapioca is made to be build for Disqus once and used multiple times by developers as opposed to Tortilla where every time you want to integrate with Disqus you need to refer to the documentation and manually "concatenate" strings to form a url resource. Although this is a valid approach, Tapioca is made to feel like you are using a "conventional" API client rather than building endpoint urls. 
3. Since developers will only be specifying resource urls once, it's not that much of a work to write down all urls in it's complete form. Modifying this would add complexity to the process with very low gain in my opinion.

